metadata.name: A Pile, To Be Sorted #146
metadata.description:
Compartmentalization in service of clarity.
Dedicated to my Dad and, by extension, his advice.

When I get overwhelmed (which is often), I typically call my dad. He‚Äôs always got some relatable story from his life I‚Äôve never heard before, OR he hits me with the same piece of advice he‚Äôs been giving me for as long as I can remember:

‚ÄúOf course it‚Äôs hard to stay calm when you look at the pile in front of you. Every responsibility, want and obligation, is not something we‚Äôre meant to face all at once. Break it up, take on one task from the pile, and focus on that.‚Äù

This has been such a stable pattern that I often don‚Äôt need to hear him say it. I‚Äôll finish describing what‚Äôs going on and stop him before he can even start, so he doesn‚Äôt have to waste his breath on something I should know by now, it‚Äôs already helping just to remember it.

The best thing I can do for myself is to pick something out of the pile and handle it in isolation. I find that often each task will grow the pile exponentially. It‚Äôs easy to handle my health and fitness when that‚Äôs all I have to think about. But then I have to think about finances, maintaining friendships, taking care of my plants, dating, and finding time for a hobby. Each one of those things has its own nuances and complications. With all that in mind, going to the gym sounds overwhelming.

But‚Äî Going to the gym is easy. Pick one thing, focus, get it done, and watch the pile shrink. Repeat.

I‚Äôve opted to create a design which illustrates this overwhelm and demonstrates how quickly those individual tasks lose form in the pile.

Press 's' to save a .png
Press '1', '2', or '3' to change render size
Press 't' to toggle linen texture (for use printing onto textured paper or cloth)

Created by Chris McCully in October 2023 using p5.js, chroma.js, and GLSL

metadata.name: ____ - Iteration 3 #5
metadata.description:
This project is part of a larger experiment that explores and celebrates the process of making generative art by progressively releasing iterations, working towards a final release on my main account (tz1RkYY3jr1ocuPdQqrRefr5FqoawKQsmBmD). The iterations will be titled ____ - Iteration 1, ____ - Iteration 2, etc. At this point, the number of iterations has not been determined, but more information will be provided as this experiment unfolds.

The final release will only be made available to those who have collected each iteration (using an allowlist), and will be released for free.

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels.

metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #425
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. ‚ÄúThe Bugged Tree‚Äù‚Äôs code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren‚Äôt under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there‚Äôs a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan

metadata.name: Blurevich #310
metadata.description:
"Blurevich"

The painting is characterized by its non-representational style, where the rectangles are not meant to depict recognizable objects or figures. 
Instead, the blurred rectangles serve as visual elements that create a sense of movement and dynamism in the painting. 
The use of blurriness in the rectangles gives the painting a hazy and ethereal quality. 
The colors used in the painting would  be bold and striking, creating a striking contrast between the sharp edges of the rectangles and the soft, blurred edges. 
The overall effect of the painting is one of abstraction and experimentation, express our emotions.

metadata.name: Round Round #80
metadata.description:
Primarily I focused on using circles as the main element in creating compositions. It involves arranging, manipulating and combining circles to form different shapes, patterns and designs.
Here, concepts such as symmetry, balance, rhythm and repetition are often examined. I used circles of different sizes, colors, textures, and opacity to create depth and visual interest, and added compositions like squiggly lines for complexity and variety.
The possibilities are endless when it comes to circles, as they have the freedom to experiment with different techniques and styles. It can take many forms including minimal, abstract designs, mandalas (spiritual symbols), optical illusions or even representational images made entirely of circles.
By focusing on the simplicity and versatility of circles, I have created a visual approach that evokes harmony, unity, and balance while also allowing for creative expression.

Made by p5.js
s = save

metadata.name: MetaSignal: Lexicon #53
metadata.description:
The project is a reinterpretation of my previous "MetaSignal", with a different key.

Two one-dimensional 3-states cellular automata intersect to form a grid with a total of nine states.
A two-dimensional cellular automata extracts details from the grid.

This complex configuration enhances the veil of mystery surrounding how intricate and captivating structures emerge from simple random rulesets.
I invite you to search and reflect about the hidden layers of meaning, hoping you will find yours.

---

16 messages, 3 sampling methods, a small probability of receiving a broken signal.

‚Ä¢ Clicking/tapping on the canvas shows a menu to pause, resume, reverse generation direction and download the current 1080x1080 pixels frame.

Done with p5.js
Simone "OuterSilent" Ferrari | IG: @outertales | September 2023
